       "CompaktRunResult(summary='Title: University of Science and Technology of Hanoi DEPARTMENT OF INFORMATION AND COMMUNICATION TECHNOLOGY Group Project Report\\n\\nDescription:\\nThis report presents a comprehensive exploration of retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) methods within the legal domain, emphasizing the integration of knowledge graphs to enhance document retrieval and question answering systems. It covers the background and motivation for the project, reviews relevant literature, and details the materials and methods employed, including data collection, graph representation, dataset creation, and retrieval pipeline design. The work evaluates the proposed approach with specific metrics, discusses results, and concludes with insights and future directions. A user interface visualization is also developed to demonstrate the system’s practical application.\\n\\nSections:\\n- Acknowledgement\\n- Summary: This section expresses gratitude to contributors and supporting entities involved in the successful completion of the project.\\n\\n- Abstract\\n- Summary: Provides a succinct overview of the research objectives, methodology, key findings, and significance of integrating knowledge graphs in RAG for legal document processing.\\n\\n- Contents\\n- Summary: Lists the document’s chapter and section headings for easy navigation.\\n\\n- List of Figures\\n- Summary: Enumerates all figures included in the report, aiding visualization of concepts and results.\\n\\n- List of Abbreviations\\n- Summary: Defines acronyms and shorthand notations used throughout the report to improve readability.\\n\\n- List of Legal Words\\n- Summary: Clarifies specific legal terminology referenced in the document, ensuring domain-specific understanding.\\n\\n- 1 Introduction\\n- Summary: Introduces the project context by outlining the importance of efficient legal information retrieval and question answering. It discusses the background of RAG technologies, states the motivation behind incorporating knowledge graphs, and clearly enumerates the project objectives aimed at advancing legal domain applications.\\n\\n    - 1.1 Context and Background: Describes the current challenges in legal document retrieval and the potential of RAG to address these issues.\\n    \\n    - 1.2 Motivation: Highlights the need for improved accuracy and contextual understanding in legal QA systems driving the project.\\n    \\n    - 1.3 Objectives: Lists the goals including creating benchmark datasets, developing graph-based retrieval models, and building demonstrative UI tools.\\n\\n- 2 Literature Review\\n- Summary: Reviews existing studies on retrieval-augmented generation within the legal field, the role of knowledge graphs in enhancing retrieval performance, and outlines the structure of this report. It establishes the foundation and gaps that this project aims to tackle.\\n\\n    - 2.1 RAG approaches in the Legal domain: Examines prior RAG models applied to legal texts and identifies limitations.\\n    \\n    - 2.2 Knowledge Graph integrated RAG: Discusses approaches that combine knowledge graphs with RAG for better semantic understanding.\\n    \\n    - 2.3 Report Structure: Provides an overview of the report’s organization to guide readers.\\n\\n- 3 Materials & Methods\\n- Summary: Details the data sources and technical methods used to build and evaluate the system. It describes how documents were collected and transformed into graph representations, the construction of QA benchmark datasets, the design of the retrieval pipeline integrating vector and graph-based methods, and the development of a user interface for visualization.\\n\\n    - 3.1 Document Collection: Explains the strategies and sources used to gather relevant legal documents and FAQs.\\n    \\n    - 3.2 Document Graph Representation: Describes the process of representing documents as graphs to capture structural and semantic relations.\\n    \\n    - 3.3 QA Benchmark Dataset: Details the creation of question-answer datasets derived from crawled FAQs and generated content to train and test models.\\n    \\n    - 3.4 Retrieval Pipeline and Graph-Integrated Retrieval: Outlines the hybrid retrieval approach combining vector embeddings and graph retrieval methods, including chunking strategies and embedding techniques.\\n    \\n    - 3.5 Demo UI Visualization: Describes the implementation of a user-friendly interface to demonstrate query input and results presentation.\\n\\n- 4 Results & Discussion\\n- Summary: Presents the evaluation metrics used to assess retrieval and QA performance, reports on experimental outcomes, and discusses the implications, strengths, and limitations of the proposed approach.\\n\\n    - 4.1 Evaluation Metrics: Specifies measures such as accuracy, precision, recall, and others relevant to the retrieval and QA tasks.\\n    \\n    - 4.2 Results: Summarizes empirical findings demonstrating the effectiveness of integrating knowledge graphs into RAG systems.\\n    \\n    - 4.3 Discussion: Analyzes the results in context, addresses challenges encountered, and suggests possible improvements.\\n\\n- 5 UI Visualization\\n- Summary: Focuses on showcasing the functional aspects of the deployment interface that enables interactive querying and displays answers, reflecting backend capabilities in an accessible format.\\n\\n- 6 Conclusion & Future Work\\n- Summary: Concludes the report by summarizing key achievements, reinforcing the value of knowledge graph integration in legal RAG systems, and outlining prospective enhancements and research directions to further improve the model and its applications.\\n\\n- References\\n- Summary: Lists all academic and technical sources cited throughout the report, underpinning the research foundation and validation.', artifacts=CompaktRunArtifacts(markdown='## **University of Science and Technology of Hanoi DEPARTMENT OF INFORMATION AND COMMUNICATION TECHNOLOGY** \\n\\n**==> picture [317 x 167] intentionally omitted <==**\\n\\n## **Group Project Report** \\n\\n**Tax Legal Retrieval with Graph Representation Assistant [** **`EN` ]** \\n\\n**Authors:** \\n\\nPham Duy Anh Nguyen Thai Nhat Anh Le Quoc Anh Dinh Thanh Hieu Ngo Xuan Kien Nguyen The Khai **Supervisor** : Tran Giang Son – ICT Department \\n\\n```\\n-\\nID23BI14023\\n-\\nID23BI14024\\n-\\nID23BI14025\\n-\\nID22BA13132\\n-\\nID23BI14239\\n-\\nID23BI14205\\n```\\n\\nHANOI, 2025 \\n\\nTax Legal Retrieval with Graph Representation Assistant \\n\\nGroup 55 \\n\\n## **Acknowledgement** \\n\\nThis project was strongly influenced and supported by Professor Tran Giang Son, the Director of Department of Information and Communication Technology, University of Science and Technology of Hanoi (ICT-USTH). We would like to express our sincere gratitude for his thoughtful guidance, valuable recommendations, and continuous support throughout the course of this project. Without his sustained involvement and encouragement, this work would not have been completed to its present extent. \\n\\n2 \\n\\nGroup Project \\n\\nTax Legal Retrieval with Graph Representation Assistant \\n\\nGroup 55 \\n\\n## **Abstract** \\n\\nRetrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) has become a popular, widely-applied approach for grounding Large Language Models (LLM) with external knowledge. However, traditional RAG systems primarily rely on flat, stateless text chunking without hierarchical awareness, which struggles to capture the semantic structure and dense cross-referencing network in legal documents, especially Vietnamese official legal documents. \\n\\nIn this work, we propose a comprehensive end-to-end framework for graph-integrated context retrieval over a corpus of Vietnamese legal documents in the domain of fees and taxation. The proposed pipeline consists of document collection, hierarchical graph construction with explicit cross-document references, and the generation of a tailored question–answer benchmark dataset for graph-vector retrieval comparison. We evaluate multiple retrieval strategies by comparing graph-based retrieval methods with traditional vector-based similarity retrieval to evaluate our hypothesis regarding the effectiveness of graph-integrated retrieval in the Legal document system. \\n\\nExperimental results indicate that while the proposed graph-based approach does not yet consistently outperform vector retrieval in all settings, it provides improved interpretability, citation traceability, and document structural awareness. These findings highlight the potential of graph representations to address fundamental limitations of traditional legal RAG systems and suggest directions for future improvements. \\n\\n3 \\n\\nGroup Project \\n\\nTax Legal Retrieval with Graph Representation Assistant \\n\\nGroup 55 \\n\\n## **Contents** \\n\\n|**1**|**Introduction**|**Introduction**|**7**|\\n|---|---|---|---|\\n||1.1|Context and Background . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .|7|\\n||1.2|Motivation . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .|7|\\n||1.3|Objectives . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .|8|\\n|**2**|**Literature Review**||**8**|\\n||2.1|RAG approaches in the Legal domain<br>. . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .|8|\\n||2.2|Knowledge Graph integrated RAG . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .|8|\\n||2.3|Report Structure . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .|9|\\n|**3**|**Materials & Methods**||**10**|\\n||3.1|Document Collection . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .|10|\\n||3.2|Document Graph Representation . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .|12|\\n||3.3|QA Benchmark Dataset . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .|24|\\n|||3.3.1<br>Proposed data model . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .|24|\\