 -0.00878143310546875, 0.017059326171875, -0.0016851425170898438, -0.011749267578125, 0.00872039794921875, -0.00844573974609375, -0.0197296142578125, 0.033050537109375, -0.0256195068359375, 0.015655517578125, -0.001384735107421875, 0.006378173828125, -0.0292205810546875, 0.0106048583984375, 0.002071380615234375, 0.0082244873046875, 0.0029010772705078125, -0.03955078125, 0.0003216266632080078, 0.0002903938293457031, 0.0022296905517578125, 0.0232391357421875, -0.0279998779296875, -0.0238494873046875, 0.0032596588134765625, -0.0137176513671875, 0.00617218017578125, -0.02325439453125, 0.03350830078125, 0.00022459030151367188, -0.01214599609375, 0.01110076904296875, -0.02130126953125, 0.0225830078125, 0.028533935546875, 0.0045318603515625, -0.005489349365234375, 0.005218505859375, -0.0260162353515625, 0.0474853515625, 0.01329803466796875, 0.01357269287109375, 0.0193634033203125, 0.0193939208984375, -0.0223388671875, -0.004638671875, -0.01520538330078125, 0.0010433197021484375, -0.055816650390625, -0.015838623046875, 0.01074981689453125, -0.0020732879638671875, -0.0284271240234375, 0.022796630859375]), CompaktEmbeddingEntry(id='9', chunk=CompaktChunk(header=<MarkdownHeader.H2: '##'>, header_type=<MarkdownHeader.H2: '##'>, header_name='1.2 motivation', content='While Large Language Models (LLMs) show strong potential for summarizing legal texts and answering legal questions, direct use of these models often leads to problems with factual accuracy, missing citations and lack of source traceability. Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) helps address these issues by grounding model outputs in provided external legal sources. However, traditional RAG systems treat legal documents as flat text collections, where all documents and passages are indexed independently at the same level without preserving their legal role or position in the hierarchy [14]. This approach ignores important legal structure and cross-references between documents and documents’ clauses. As a result, retrieval is based only on surface, individual disconnected text chunks, making it difficult to support structured legal reasoning or produce verifiable, legally valid citations [13].  \\nThese limitations have motivated the exploration of graph representations that explicitly model legal hierarchies and inter-document relationships. By encoding document levels and cross-node edges, recent proposed approaches design a Graph representation of legal documents based on Natural Language Processing (NLP) and the assistance of LLMs for graph construction. However, we identify a notable research gap in existing work on graph-integrated retrieval for legal documents. Most comprehensive and recent approaches to graph-based retrieval, such as [28] and [38], are developed and evaluated primarily for non-Vietnamese languages, and their assumptions may not directly apply to the Vietnamese legal context. Conversely, existing Vietnamese studies in this area remain limited in scope. For instance, [26] focuses specifically on legal statute cases without addressing broader legal document types, while [27], despite constructing a detailed and thorough graph representation of Vietnamese legal documents, does not focus on extending the resulting graph to support graph-integrated embeddings or retrieval strategies.  \\nOur proposed approach addresses this research gap by inheriting and extending graph representation strategies from prior works and applying graph-based embedding and information retrieval methods explicitly fostered by graph integration. Moreover, we construct our own customized training dataset and deliberately minimize dependence on black box LLMs, instead focusing on task-specific Deep Learning models for information extraction and graph retrieval strategies.  \\n7  \\nGroup Project  \\nTax Legal Retrieval with Graph Representation Assistant  \\nGroup 55', metadata={'header_2': '**1.2 Motivation**'}), embedding=[-0.01435089111328125, 0.037384033203125, 0.02728271484375, -0.