 hierarchical organization of legal documents and language-specific tokenization features. To address these challenges, several studies have proposed enhancements to data preprocessing and retrieval strategies. For example, [12] improves retrieval performance through refined data processing and retrieval fusion, combining semantic search, hybrid retrieval strategies, and re-ranking methods. Similarly, [19] optimize multistage retrieval pipelines to dynamically improve retrieval quality.  \\nDespite these advances, existing approaches operate on flattened text chunks and remain limited in their ability to explicitly interpret hierarchical structure. In particular, they lack awareness of the hierarchical position of retrieved contexts, do not incorporate cross-document or cross-clause references, and provide limited support for transparent citation in the generation phase [38] [13] [14]. These limitations have motivated the adoption of graph-based representations.', metadata={'header_2': '**2.1 RAG approaches in the Legal domain**'}), embedding=[0.004817962646484375, 0.049224853515625, 0.0229034423828125, 0.0200042724609375, 0.0057373046875, -0.0105133056640625, -0.02325439453125, -0.012237548828125, -0.01229095458984375, 0.0211029052734375, 0.0023784637451171875, -0.0445556640625, -0.0168914794921875, -0.005279541015625, 0.01279449462890625, 0.0005826950073242188, 0.036346435546875, -0.0114898681640625, -0.00016951560974121094, 0.036468505859375, 0.028045654296875, -0.00719451904296875, 0.044891357421875, 0.025390625, -0.0036792755126953125, -0.035614013671875, 0.0294342041015625, 0.042327880859375, 0.0012826919555664062, -0.027374267578125, 0.0159912109375, -0.0239105224609375, 0.01267242431640625, -0.017547607421875, 0.00493621826171875, 0.05645751953125, -0.0190887451171875, -0.0246124267578125, -0.00920867919921875, 0.026641845703125, 0.0213775634765625, -0.0038089752197265625, 0.0106964111328125, 0.03106689453125, -0.011932373046875, 0.0191650390625, -0.01676940