-0.01678466796875, -0.048248291015625, 0.022430419921875, -0.0177001953125, -0.026702880859375, 0.0001348257064819336, 0.0215911865234375, 0.00431060791015625, -0.033172607421875, -0.01407623291015625, -0.01910400390625]), CompaktEmbeddingEntry(id='44', chunk=CompaktChunk(header=<MarkdownHeader.H2: '##'>, header_type=<MarkdownHeader.H2: '##'>, header_name='graph retrieval', content='For graph retrieval, we first facilitated baseline retrieval strategies based on **embedding similarity** (dense representation) and **exact keyword matching** (sparse representation), as well as a combined approach that performs exact word match followed by a re-ranking step using embedding similarity, following the proposed retrieval technique from [29]. We additionally implemented a hybrid ranker that jointly leverages dense and sparse feature representations. These methods closely resemble traditional retrieval approaches, with the primary distinction being that the embeddings are already enriched with graph node relational information. To align the query embedding with the output space of the gated fusion module, which integrates contextual and graph-structural information by an MLP layer, we introduced two adaptive strategies.  \\n- In the first approach, the textual embedding of the input prompt is fused with a zero vector representing the initial absence of graph structure, yielding a combined representation in the joint embedding space.  \\n- In the second approach, the top-k contexts are first retrieved using exact lexical matching and the positional embeddings from these contexts are mean-pooled. This resulting pooled vector serves as a pseudo-positional embedding that maps the input prompt to a virtual location in the graph based on its lexically-related neighbors, which is then fused with the textual embedding to produce the final representation to be applied for second-turn similarity search.  \\nBeyond basic node retrieval, we utilized the fundamental property of graph, being the **Graph Traversal** . After retrieving an initial set of candidate nodes, we expanded the retrieval scope by incorporating their neighboring nodes within k-hops (i.e., direct neighbors and neighbors of neighbors), subject to a maximum of n nodes. The retrieved nodes are ordered by node ID and concatenated with the original node text to construct the final chunk result. This strategy captures both node-specific information and local neighborhood context within a single contextual chunk.  \\n**==> picture [227 x 150] intentionally omitted <==**  \\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\\n3<br>HAS_POINT<br>HAS_SUBPOINT<br>1 2 4<br>0<br>5<br>HAS_CLAUSE<br>HAS_SUBPOINT<br>HAS_SUBPOINT<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>  \\n**Figure 16:** Sample Graph Traversal, the system first retrieves Node 2 then collects the top 5 nodes within 2 hops neighboring nodes (0, 1, 3, 4, 5) ranked by node ID and concatenates all of the text into 1 chunk  \\n33  \\nGroup Project  \\nTax Legal Retrieval with Graph Representation Assistant  \\nGroup 55', metadata={'header_2': '**Graph Retrieval**'}), embedding=[-0.03173828125, 0.0252838134765625, 0.0555419921875, -0.006755828857421875, 0.00478363037109375, 0.000640869140625, -0.006221771240234375, 0.0207366943359375, -0.030426025390625, 0.0265655517578125, 0.0166778564453125, -0.0791015625, -0.0117950439453125, -0.033599853515625, 0.02130126953125, -0.006969451904296875, 0.03228759765625, -0.01381683349609375, -0.01995849609375, 0.030487060546875, 0.031341552734375, -0.0408935546875, -0.01486968994140625, -0.006153106689453125, -0.0134124755859375, -0.01259613037109375, 0.0290374755859375, 0.030029296875, 0.04779052734375, -0.00518798828125, -0.025726318359375, -0.04095458984375, -0.0279998779296875, -0.013336181640625, -0.01212310791015625, 0.04754638671875, -0.046722412109375, 0.01470184326171875, -0.001583099365234375, 0.0217132568359375, 0.044769287109375, 0.0261077880859375, -0.0148162841796875, 0.0015172958374023438, 