9208984375, -0.01511383056640625, 0.01103973388671875, 0.08642578125, 0.004123687744140625, -0.0011529922485351562, -0.0237579345703125, 0.0017518997192382812, -0.030059814453125, 0.032318115234375, 0.034454345703125, 0.03509521484375, -0.0282440185546875, 0.030517578125, 0.007534027099609375, 0.0182342529296875, 0.038177490234375, 0.021392822265625, 0.0272216796875, -0.029998779296875, -0.0276031494140625, -0.0136871337890625, -0.0060882568359375, 0.0012569427490234375, 0.0484619140625, -0.0214691162109375, 0.003025054931640625, 0.016082763671875, -0.0113067626953125, 0.0129547119140625, 0.0146636962890625, -0.0032215118408203125, 0.01105499267578125, 1.5616416931152344e-05, 0.0064849853515625, 0.0026073455810546875, -0.0024871826171875, -0.0211944580078125, 0.016693115234375, -0.0352783203125, 0.005329132080078125, -0.00829315185546875, -0.0132904052734375, 0.006946563720703125, 0.023895263671875, -0.00791168212890625, 0.0023746490478515625, -0.007007598876953125, -0.04620361328125, 0.018310546875, -0.018798828125, 0.03240966796875, -0.0273284912109375, -0.01192474365234375, -0.01226043701171875, -0.03155517578125, -0.0032978057861328125, -0.0160064697265625, -0.028564453125, 0.041412353515625, 0.0007834434509277344, 0.0330810546875, -0.0217742919921875, 0.006450653076171875, 0.0002512931823730469, 0.0007958412170410156, 0.01010894775390625, -0.030426025390625]), CompaktEmbeddingEntry(id='46', chunk=CompaktChunk(header=<MarkdownHeader.H2: '##'>, header_type=<MarkdownHeader.H2: '##'>, header_name='4.1 evaluation metrics', content='To assess the performance of the Retrieval approaches, we defined the set of three benchmark evaluation metrics from several RAG studies [38] [39], namely **Precision** , **Recall** , and **Mean Reciprocal Rank (MRR)** . Recent research about RAG optimization has established these metrics as the standard for evaluating retrieval performance; however, our project utilizes these metrics primarily as a shared baseline for assessing the performance of our approaches instead of directly comparing with other researches due to scale mismatches.  \\nRetrieval evaluation does not involve a negative class; instead, it focuses on whether an item is _relevant_ to the golden contexts. Given a list of contexts retrieved by the retrieval model and a corresponding list of referenced contexts representing the ideal (ground-truth) set, the evaluation metrics are defined as follows:  \\n**==> picture [262 x 26] intentionally omitted <==**  \\n_Precision_ = _[|][Retrieved]_[_] _[Context][ ∩][Re][f][erenced]_[_] _[Context][|] Retrieved_  Context_  \\n**Recall** measures the proportion of referenced contexts covered and supported by retrieved information. **Precision** , in contrast, measures the proportion of retrieved contexts that directly support the gold referenced contexts, penalizing the retrieval of irrelevant or unsupporting contexts. These metrics operate in a complementary trade-off, particularly in greedy retrieval settings where increasing the number of top-k retrieved contexts generally leads to higher recall, as more relevant contexts are likely to be included; however, this increase comes at the cost of reduced precision due to the introduction of a larger number of irrelevant contexts.  \\nA distinct aspect of these metrics is the inter-entity cross-comparison between two lists, where the notation _∩_ denotes **Relevance** between entities from each list. Recent studies have proposed various methods to approach this notion of relevance. For instance, some GraphRAG-based works, such as [38], construct graph-supported benchmark datasets with consistent context chunk identifiers, enabling direct comparison between retrieved and reference identifier lists. In contrast, other studies leverage large language models (LLMs) like the recently introduced **Retrieval Augmented Generation Assessment** (RAGAS) library to infer relevance relationships using richer semantic features, particularly in scenarios where explicit node or chunk identifiers are unavailable. We adopted a thresholded similarity-score approach inspired by RAGAS to support both vector-based retrieval (text-based, stateless chunking) and graph-based retrieval (hierarchical structure with explicit node identifiers). Specifically, a shared embedding model was used to encode both retrieved contexts and reference contexts into a shared embedding space. Pairwise similarity scores were then computed, and a relevance flag was assigned when the similarity score exceeds a predefined threshold, in this study, we benchmarked the PhoBERT-base model as the judge embedding model and adopted a similarity threshold of 0.7 to capture a broad range of result patterns while maintaining a high baseline for Relevancy.  \\nIn addition to Recall and Precision, we also evaluated **Mean Reciprocal Rank (MRR)** , which exploits the ranked nature of retrieval systems by assigning higher scores when relevant contexts are retrieved at earlier ranks.  \\n**==> picture [100 x 35] intentionally omitted <==**  \\nWhere _i_ is the Rank of the first _Relevant_ retrieved context to any referenced context.  \\n36  \\nGroup Project  \\nTax Legal Retrieval with Graph Representation Assistant  \\nGroup 55', metadata={'header_2': '**4.1 Evaluation Metrics**'}), embedding=[-0.0083770751953125, 0.0276947021484375, 0.050994873046875, -0.0032863616943359375, -0.01044464111328125, 0.0087127685546875, -0.005069732666015625, 0.0186309814453125, -0.0413818359375, 0.000209808349609375, 0.011016845703125, -0.056304931640625, -0.00444793701171875, -0.0205230712890625, 0.0325927734375, 0.003253936767578125, 0.0145263671875, -0.042755126953125, -0.04400634765625, 0.037841796875, 0.02239990234375, -0.02099609375, 0.007415771484375, -0.0030956268310546875, -0.01239013671875, -0.033599853515625, 0.051788330078125, 0.0413818359375, 0.047332763671875, -0.007625579833984375, -0.0028705596923828125, -0.032958984375, -0.04498291015625, -0.004062652587890625, -0.02009582